{"id":"1411.4036","submitter":"Sergio Boixo","authors":"Sergio Boixo and Vadim N. Smelyanskiy and Alireza Shabani and Sergei\n  V. Isakov and Mark Dykman and Vasil S. Denchev and Mohammad Amin and Anatoly\n  Smirnov and Masoud Mohseni and Hartmut Neven","title":"Computational Role of Collective Tunneling in a Quantum Annealer","comments":"Many minor updates, results unchanged. 33 pages, 35 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Quantum tunneling is a phenomenon in which a quantum state traverses energy\nbarriers above the energy of the state itself. Tunneling has been hypothesized\nas an advantageous physical resource for optimization. Here we present the\nfirst experimental evidence of a computational role of multiqubit quantum\ntunneling in the evolution of a programmable quantum annealer. We develop a\ntheoretical model based on a NIBA Quantum Master Equation to describe the\nmultiqubit dissipative tunneling effects under the complex noise\ncharacteristics of such quantum devices. We start by considering a\ncomputational primitive, an optimization problem consisting of just one global\nand one false minimum. The quantum evolutions enable tunneling to the global\nminimum while the corresponding classical paths are trapped in a false minimum.\nIn our study the non-convex potentials are realized by frustrated networks of\nqubit clusters with strong intra-cluster coupling. We show that the collective\neffect of the quantum environment is suppressed in the \"critical\" phase during\nthe evolution where quantum tunneling \"decides\" the right path to solution. In\na later stage dissipation facilitates the multiqubit tunneling leading to the\nsolution state. The predictions of the model accurately describe the\nexperimental data from the D-Wave Two quantum annealer at NASA Ames. In our\ncomputational primitive the temperature dependence of the probability of\nsuccess in the quantum model is opposite to that of the classical paths with\nthermal hopping. Specifically, we provide an analysis of an optimization\nproblem with sixteen qubits, demonstrating eight qubit tunneling that increases\nsuccess probabilities. Furthermore, we report results for larger problems with\nup to 200 qubits that contain the primitive as subproblems.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 14 Nov 2014 20:43:41 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 19 Feb 2015 01:30:08 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-02-20"}
